readme.md
    20вҶ’## Benefits over plain `fetch`
    22вҶ’- Simpler API
    23вҶ’- Method shortcuts (`ky.post()`)
    24вҶ’- Treats non-2xx status codes as errors (after redirects)
    25вҶ’- Retries failed requests
    26вҶ’- JSON option
    27вҶ’- Timeout support
    28вҶ’- URL prefix option
    29вҶ’- Instances with custom defaults
    30вҶ’- Hooks
    31вҶ’- TypeScript niceties (e.g. `.json()` supports generics and defaults to `unknown`, not `any`)
    32вҶ’
    33вҶ’## Install
    35вҶ’```sh
    36вҶ’npm install ky
    37вҶ’```
    38вҶ’
    39вҶ’###### CDN
    45вҶ’## Usage
    47вҶ’```js
    48вҶ’import ky from 'ky';
    49вҶ’
    50вҶ’const json = await ky.post('https://example.com', {json: {foo: true}}).json();
    51вҶ’
    52вҶ’console.log(json);
    53вҶ’//=> {data: 'рҹҰ„'}
    54вҶ’```
    55вҶ’
    56вҶ’With plain `fetch`, it would be:
    57вҶ’
    58вҶ’```js
    59вҶ’class HTTPError extends Error {}
    60вҶ’
    61вҶ’const response = await fetch('https://example.com', {
    62вҶ’	method: 'POST',
    63вҶ’	body: JSON.stringify({foo: true}),
    64вҶ’	headers: {
    65вҶ’		'content-type': 'application/json'
    66вҶ’	}
    67вҶ’});
    68вҶ’
    69вҶ’if (!response.ok) {
    70вҶ’	throw new HTTPError(`Fetch error: ${response.statusText}`);
    71вҶ’}
    72вҶ’
    73вҶ’const json = await response.json();
    74вҶ’
    75вҶ’console.log(json);
    76вҶ’//=> {data: 'рҹҰ„'}
    77вҶ’```
    78вҶ’
